Theoretical Investigation of Externally Pressurized Air-Suspension Conveyer With Multiple Supply Holes
items.abstract: <jats:p>The externally pressurized air suspension conveyer is investigated theoretically. The supporting area of the conveyer is comparatively large, and has multiple air supply holes, whose positions may vary due to the relative motion of the article and the supporting surface. The analysis is made under the assumption of semi infinite area of supported surface with the discrete supply holes of the conveyer, and thereafter, with equivalent air feeding distributed over the conveyer surface. The case of the circular pad is analyzed as well in order to take into account the effect of the finite supported surface area. The distributed air feeding solution agrees well with the discrete supply hole solution as well as with experimental results.</jats:p>

container-title: JAWRA Journal of the American Water Resources Association
items.abstract: <jats:title>ABSTRACT</jats:title><jats:p>A general sketch of the important role of the Sacramento‐San Joaquin Delta in the redistribution of the water supply of the State of California. Paper includes a brief description of the role of the Bureau of Reclamation and California Department of Water Resources in the state's water development, describing major units of the Federal Central Valley Project, State Water Project and evolution of the Federal‐State Peripheral Canal Unit proposed for moving water supplies around the Delta. Environmental problems associated with movement of water supplies around and/or through the Delta are briefly enumerated.</jats:p>
